	abstract = {Smart cities have been recognized as a promising research focus around the world. To realize smart cities, how to effectively compute and utilize of big data are the key factors. More specifically, exploring the patterns of human mobility based on large amounts of multi-source data plays an important role in analyzing the formation of social-economic phenomena in smart cities. However, our acquired knowledge is still very limited for smart cities. In this article, we propose an integrated computing method to rescale heterogeneous traffic trajectory data, which leverages Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE) and Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC). Our analysis is based on two real datasets generated by subway smart card transactions and taxi GPS trajectories from Shanghai in China, which contain more than 451 million trading records by 14 subway lines and 34 billion GPS records by 13,695 taxis respectively. Especially, we quantitatively explore the patterns of human mobility on weekends and weekdays respectively. Through logarithmic binning and data fitness, we calculate the Bayesian weights to select the best fitting distributions. In addition, we leverage three metrics to analyze the patterns of human mobility in two datasets i.e., trip displacement, trip duration, and trip interval. We obtain several important human mobility patterns and discover quite a few interesting phenomena, which lay a solid foundation for future research.},
